Chapter 10.

Methods of divination.

1. auspicia sortesque: the former is the broader term and includes the several methods of divination mentioned in the chapter exclusive of the lot. Recall Caesar, Bellum Gallicum 1. 50. 4 (quoted in note on 8. 7), where we are told that the German matrons resorted to the lot in order to discover the propitious time for battle; also 1. 53. 7, in which it is narrated that the Germans had recourse to the lots three times to deter- mine the fate of Valerius Procillus, a friend of Caesar held captive by Ariovistus. — ut qui maxime: elliptical for ut ii qui maxime observant. — sortium: divination by lot was so wide- spread as to amount to a folk custom in antiquity. The prac- tice existed among pcoples so far separated as Scythians, Celts, Italiam, Finns‚ and Teutons. Among the Italians Caere, Falerii, and Patavium were centers of the process and the sortes of the temple of Fortune at Praeneste were especially famous. Cicero, De Divinatione 2. 41. 85—87, flouts the method as a tissue of fraud; nevertheless the sortileyus continued to be a feature of the life of Augustan and imperial Rome3 cf. Horace, Satires 1. 9. 29 f.; Tibullus, 1. 3. 11-12; Juvenal, 6. 583; Apuleius, Metamorphoses 9. 8.

2. simplex: ‘conform—virgam: wood, since it was most readily obtainable and easily incised, was the material most used for the sortes among primitive peoples.
